{"title_page": "HAS University of Applied Sciences", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = HAS University of Applied Sciences\n| image_size = 300px\n| caption = Logo of HAS University of Applied Sciences\n| motto = The University of agribusiness, food and living environment\n| established = 1947\n| type = [[Public university|Public]]\n| chairman = Dick Pouwels\n| students = 3400\n| city = [['s-Hertogenbosch]] and [[Venlo]]\n| country = [[Netherlands]]\n| website = http://www.hasuniversity.nl/\n| staff = 450\n}}\n[[image:HAS Den Bosch & Stoas Hogeschool.jpg|thumb|300px|HAS University of Applied Sciences building[['s-Hertogenbosch]]]]\n\n'''HAS University of Applied Sciences''' ({{lang-nl|HAS Hogeschool}}) is an independent university of [[applied sciences]], specialising in [[food]], [[agriculture]], [[horticulture]], [[conservation (ethic)|nature]] and [[natural Environment|environment]]. It is located in [['s-Hertogenbosch]], the regional capital of [[North Brabant]] and [[Venlo]], [[Limburg (Netherlands)|Limburg]]. All bachelor programmes are accredited by the [[NVAO|Dutch Flemish Accreditation Organisation]]. In 2017 there were around 3400 students enrolled at HAS University of Applied Sciences.\n\n== History ==\nOn 13 October 1947 MLS (middelbare landbouwschool) was opened in [[Roermond]], and  followed a year later by the MZS (middelbare landbouwschool). In 1956 the higher horticulture school was opened in [[Nijmegen]], which  became part of HAS (hogere agrarische scholen gemeenschap) which formed the KNBTB (Koninklijke Nederlandse Boeren- en Tuindersbond) in 's-Hertogenbosch, North Brabant in 1962. This was later renamed to HAS University of Applied Sciences. In 2013 HAS University of Applied Sciences opened their 2nd location in Venlo, Limburg.\n\n== Studyprogrammes ==\nHAS University of Applied Sciences offers 9 Dutch-taught [[Bachelor's degree|bachelor]] programmes and 3 English-taught Bachelor programmes.\n\n{| \n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:red\" align=\"center\" |'''HAS University of Applied Sciences'''\n|-bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"\n| rowspan=\"4\"|Dutch Courses\n| rowspan=\"6\"|Bachelor Courses||Animal Husbandry||Food Innovation||Spatial & Environmental Planning\n|-bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"\n| Horticulture & Arable Farming||Food Technology||Environmental Science\n|-bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"\n| Business Administration & Agri-foodbusiness||||Applied Biology\n|-bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"\n||||| Geo Media & Design\n|-bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n| rowspan=\"5\"|English Courses||Horticulture & Business Management||International Food & Agribusiness||\n|-bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n| Business Management in Agriculture & Food||||\n|-bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n|-bgcolor=\"purple\"\n|}\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2016 Elsevier 'Best University of Applied Sciences of the Netherlands' award\n* 2017 Keuzegids HBO: 2nd best University of Applied Sciences (medium size)\n* 2018 Keuzegids HBO: 2nd best University of Applied Sciences (medium size)\n\n== HAS Training and Consultancy ==\nHAS Training and Consultancy (Dutch: HAS Kennistransfer en Bedrijfsopleidingen), a partner of HAS University of Applied Sciences, offers [https://has.nl/en/abouthas/training-and-consultancy research and consultancy services], training programs, courses and [https://has.nl/en/training SPOC's] for business and government organizations in the agribusiness and the food sector. HAS Training and Consultancy allows international students of HAS University of Applied Sciences to participate in research as part of their graduation projects, under the supervision of a consultant.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.hasuniversity.nl/ HAS University of Applied Sciences - Student website]\n* [https://has.nl/en HAS University of Applied Sciences -] [https://has.nl/en Corporate website]\n* [http://www.has.nl/en/training HAS Knowledge Transfer and Training]\n* {{in lang|nl}} [http://www.gremio-unio.nl/ HAS student association]\n\n{{coord|51|41|10.96|N|5|17|08.06|E|region:NL-GE_type:landmark_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n{{Dutch Vocational Universities}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Has Den Bosch}}\n[[Category:Vocational universities in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Agricultural universities and colleges in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Horticultural organizations]]\n[[Category:Education in North Brabant|HAS University of Applied Sciences]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in 's-Hertogenbosch|HAS University of Applied Sciences]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = HAS University of Applied Sciences\n| image_size = 300px\n| caption = Logo of HAS University of Applied Sciences\n| motto = The University of agribusiness, food and living environment\n| established = 1947\n| type = [[Public university|Public]]\n| chairman = Dick Pouwels\n| students = 3400\n| city = [['s-Hertogenbosch]] and [[Venlo]]\n| country = [[Netherlands]]\n| website = http://www.hasuniversity.nl/\n| staff = 450\n}}\n[[image:HAS Den Bosch & Stoas Hogeschool.jpg|thumb|300px|HAS University of Applied Sciences building[['s-Hertogenbosch]]]]\n\n'''HAS University of Applied Sciences''' ({{lang-nl|HAS Hogeschool}}) is an independent university of [[applied sciences]], specialising in [[food]], [[agriculture]], [[horticulture]], [[conservation (ethic)|nature]] and [[natural Environment|environment]]. It is located in [['s-Hertogenbosch]], the regional capital of [[North Brabant]] and [[Venlo]], [[Limburg (Netherlands)|Limburg]]. All bachelor programmes are accredited by the [[NVAO|Dutch Flemish Accreditation Organisation]]. In 2017 there were around 3400 students enrolled at HAS University of Applied Sciences.\n\n== History ==\nOn 13 October 1947 MLS (middelbare landbouwschool) was opened in [[Roermond]], and  followed a year later by the MZS (middelbare landbouwschool). In 1956 the higher horticulture school was opened in [[Nijmegen]], which  became part of HAS (hogere agrarische scholen gemeenschap) which formed the KNBTB (Koninklijke Nederlandse Boeren- en Tuindersbond) in 's-Hertogenbosch, North Brabant in 1962. This was later renamed to HAS University of Applied Sciences. In 2013 HAS University of Applied Sciences opened their 2nd location in Venlo, Limburg. \n\n== Studyprogrammes ==\nHAS University of Applied Sciences offers 9 Dutch-taught [[Bachelor's degree|bachelor]] programmes and 3 English-taught Bachelor programmes.\n\n{| \n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:red\" align=\"center\" |'''HAS University of Applied Sciences'''\n|-bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"\n| rowspan=\"4\"|Dutch Courses\n| rowspan=\"6\"|Bachelor Courses||Animal Husbandry||Food Innovation||Spatial & Environmental Planning\n|-bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"\n| Horticulture & Arable Farming||Food Technology||Environmental Science\n|-bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"\n| Business Administration & Agri-foodbusiness||||Applied Biology\n|-bgcolor=\"lightgreen\"\n||||| Geo Media & Design\n|-bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n| rowspan=\"5\"|English Courses||Horticulture & Business Management||International Food & Agribusiness||\n|-bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n| Business Management in Agriculture & Food||||\n|-bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n|-bgcolor=\"purple\"\n|}\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2016 Elsevier 'Best University of Applied Sciences of the Netherlands' award\n* 2017 Keuzegids HBO: 2nd best University of Applied Sciences (medium size)\n* 2018 Keuzegids HBO: 2nd best University of Applied Sciences (medium size)\n\n== HAS Training and Consultancy ==\nHAS Training and Consultancy (Dutch: HAS Kennistransfer en Bedrijfsopleidingen), a partner of HAS University of Applied Sciences, offers [https://has.nl/en/abouthas/training-and-consultancy research and consultancy services], training programs, courses and [https://has.nl/en/training SPOC's] for business and government organizations in the agribusiness and the food sector. HAS Training and Consultancy allows international students of HAS University of Applied Sciences to participate in research as part of their graduation projects, under the supervision of a consultant.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.hasuniversity.nl/ HAS University of Applied Sciences - Student website]\n* [https://has.nl/en HAS University of Applied Sciences -] [https://has.nl/en Corporate website]\n* [http://www.has.nl/en/training HAS Knowledge Transfer and Training]\n* {{in lang|nl}} [http://www.gremio-unio.nl/ HAS student association]\n\n{{coord|51|41|10.96|N|5|17|08.06|E|region:NL-GE_type:landmark_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n{{Dutch Vocational Universities}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Has Den Bosch}}\n[[Category:Vocational universities in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Agricultural universities and colleges in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Horticultural organizations]]\n[[Category:Education in North Brabant|HAS University of Applied Sciences]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in 's-Hertogenbosch|HAS University of Applied Sciences]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HAS_University_of_Applied_Sciences"}
{"title_page": "Secretary of State for International Development", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox official post\n| post = Secretary\n| body = State for International Development\n| flag = \n| flagsize = \n| flagcaption = \n| insignia = Royal Coat of Arms of the United Kingdom (HM Government).svg\n| insigniacaption = [[Royal coat of arms of the United Kingdom|Royal Arms]] of [[Her Majesty's Government]]\n| image = Official portrait of Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan crop 2.jpg\n| incumbent = [[Anne-Marie Trevelyan]]\n| incumbentsince = 13 February 2020\n| department = [[Department for International Development]]\n| style = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| residence = \n| nominator = \n| appointer = The [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|Monarch]]\n| appointer_qualified = on advice of the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]]\n| termlength = \n| first = [[Barbara Castle]]\n| formation = 18 October 1964\n| deputy = [[Minister of State for International Development]]\n| salary = \n| website = {{url|www.dfid.gov.uk}}\n}}\n{{PoliticsUK}}\n\n'''Her Majesty's Principal Secretary of State for International Development''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[cabinet of the United Kingdom|cabinet]] minister responsible for the [[Department for International Development]] and for promoting development overseas, particularly in [[developing countries]]. The post was created in 1997 when the Department for International Development was made independent of the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] (FCO).\n\nA separate Ministry of Overseas Development was established by [[Harold Wilson]] when he came to office in 1964.  The first three holders of the office served in the Cabinet, but from 29 August 1967 the office was demoted.  Under [[Edward Heath]], the Ministry was re-incorporated into the FCO on 15 October 1970.  Wilson again established the Ministry in 1974, but later merged it into the FCO once again: from 10 June 1975 to 8 October 1979 the Foreign Secretary served as Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs and Minister for Overseas Development in the cabinet, while the Minister for Overseas Development held the rank of Minister of State within the Foreign and Commonwealth Office.  The Minister of State had day-to-day responsibility. Under the Labour government of the 1970s, Reg Prentice sat in the Cabinet during his term.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dfid.gov.uk/About-DFID/History1/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20101011133338/http%3A//www.dfid.gov.uk/About%2DDFID/History1/ |archivedate=11 October 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==List of Ministers and Secretaries of State==\n\n===Ministers of Overseas Development (1964\u20131970)===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Minister of Overseas Development\n! colspan=2|Name\n! colspan=2|Term of office\n! Party\n! colspan=2|Prime Minister\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Barbara Castle]]\n| 18 October 1964\n| 23 December 1965\n| [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| rowspan=5 style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| rowspan=5|[[Harold Wilson]]\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Anthony Greenwood, Baron Greenwood of Rossendale|Anthony Greenwood]]\n| 23 December 1965\n| 11 August 1966\n| Labour\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Arthur Bottomley]]\n| 11 August 1966\n| 29 August 1967\n| Labour\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Reg Prentice, Baron Prentice|Reginald Prentice]]\n| 29 August 1967\n| 6 October 1969\n| Labour\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Judith Hart, Baroness Hart of South Lanark|Judith Hart]]\n| 6 October 1969\n| 19 June 1970\n| Labour\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Richard Wood, Baron Holderness|Richard Wood]]\n| 23 June 1970\n| 15 October 1970\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Edward Heath]]\n|}\n\n===Ministers for Overseas Development (1970\u20131997)===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Minister for Overseas Development at the Foreign and Commonwealth Office\n! colspan=2|Name\n! colspan=2|Term of office\n! Party\n! colspan=2|Prime Minister\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Richard Wood, Baron Holderness|Richard Wood]]\n| 15 October 1970\n| 4 March 1974\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Edward Heath]]\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Judith Hart]]\n| 7 March 1974\n| 10 June 1975\n| [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| rowspan=2 style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| rowspan=2|[[Harold Wilson]]\n|-\n! rowspan=2 style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| rowspan=2|[[Reginald Prentice]]\n| rowspan=2|10 June 1975\n| rowspan=2| 21 December 1976<br>(resigned)\n| rowspan=2|Labour\n|-\n| rowspan=3 style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| rowspan=3|[[James Callaghan]]\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Frank Judd, Baron Judd|Frank Judd]]\n| 21 December 1976\n| 21 February 1977\n| Labour\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Judith Hart]]\n| 21 February 1977\n| 4 May 1979\n| Labour\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Neil Marten]]\n| 6 May 1979\n| 6 January 1983\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| rowspan=4 style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| rowspan=4|[[Margaret Thatcher]]\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Tim Raison]]\n| 