ponsible for the [[Department for International Development]] and for promoting development overseas, particularly in [[developing countries]]. The post was created in 1997 when the Department for International Development was made independent of the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] (FCO).\n\nA separate Ministry of Overseas Development was established by [[Harold Wilson]] when he came to office in 1964.  The first three holders of the office served in the Cabinet, but from 29 August 1967 the office was demoted.  Under [[Edward Heath]], the Ministry was re-incorporated into the FCO on 15 October 1970.  Wilson again established the Ministry in 1974, but later merged it into the FCO once again: from 10 June 1975 to 8 October 1979 the Foreign Secretary served as '''Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs and Minister for Overseas Development''' in the cabinet, while the Minister for Overseas Development held the rank of Minister of State within the Foreign and Commonwealth Office.  The Minister of State had day-to-day responsibility. Under the Labour government of the 1970s, Reg Prentice sat in the Cabinet during his term.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dfid.gov.uk/About-DFID/History1/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20101011133338/http%3A//www.dfid.gov.uk/About%2DDFID/History1/ |archivedate=11 October 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==List of Ministers and Secretaries of State==\n\n===Ministers of Overseas Development (1964\u20131970)===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Minister of Overseas Development\n! colspan=2|Name\n! colspan=2|Term of office\n! Party\n! colspan=2|Prime Minister\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Barbara Castle]]\n| 18 October 1964\n| 23 December 1965\n| [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| rowspan=5 style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| rowspan=5|[[Harold Wilson]]\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Anthony Greenwood, Baron Greenwood of Rossendale|Anthony Greenwood]]\n| 23 December 1965\n| 11 August 1966\n| Labour\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Arthur Bottomley]]\n| 11 August 1966\n| 29 August 1967\n| Labour\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Reg Prentice, Baron Prentice|Reginald Prentice]]\n| 29 August 1967\n| 6 October 1969\n| Labour\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Judith Hart, Baroness Hart of South Lanark|Judith Hart]]\n| 6 October 1969\n| 19 June 1970\n| Labour\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Richard Wood, Baron Holderness|Richard Wood]]\n| 23 June 1970\n| 15 October 1970\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Edward Heath]]\n|}\n\n===Ministers for Overseas Development (1970\u20131997)===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Minister for Overseas Development at the Foreign and Commonwealth Office\n! colspan=2|Name\n! colspan=2|Term of office\n! Party\n! colspan=2|Prime Minister\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Richard Wood, Baron Holderness|Richard Wood]]\n| 15 October 1970\n| 4 March 1974\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Edward Heath]]\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Judith Hart]]\n| 7 March 1974\n| 10 June 1975\n| [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| rowspan=2 style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| rowspan=2|[[Harold Wilson]]\n|-\n! rowspan=2 style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| rowspan=2|[[Reginald Prentice]]\n| rowspan=2|10 June 1975\n| rowspan=2| 21 December 1976<br>(resigned)\n| rowspan=2|Labour\n|-\n| rowspan=3 style=\"background-c